#compdef dumi
# =============================================================================
# dumi — Umi.js team's "Documentation Generator of React
#        Component" — a TypeScript-Node CLI for building
#        static documentation sites for React component
#        libraries.  Built on Umi 4 (React framework) +
#        Webpack 5 / Vite, with markdown-driven content,
#        live JSX preview, automatic API table generation
#        from TypeScript types, multi-language support, and
#        first-class component playground integration.
#        Distinguishing from Docusaurus, VitePress, Storybook,
#        Nextra, and other docs tools by:
#          - REACT-COMPONENT-FIRST DESIGN — dumi is purpose-
#            built for documenting React component libraries
#            (Ant Design, Pro Components, ahooks, formily,
#            DvaJS, etc.).  Other tools are framework-agnostic
#            (Docusaurus) or framework-specific to other
#            ecosystems (VitePress for Vue, Storybook for any).
#          - LIVE JSX PLAYGROUND — inline Markdown code blocks
#            tagged ```jsx live become interactive component
#            demos with editable source + live preview:
#              ```jsx live
#              import { Button } from 'antd';
#              export default () => <Button type="primary">OK</Button>;
#              ```
#          - AUTO API TABLES — `<API src="./Component.tsx" />`
#            JSX directive auto-generates prop tables from
#            TypeScript types + JSDoc comments
#          - .dumirc.ts CONFIG via TypeScript — type-safe
#            configuration file (.dumirc.ts or .dumirc.js):
#              import { defineConfig } from 'dumi';
#              export default defineConfig({
#                themeConfig: { name: 'My Library' },
#                navs: [{ title: 'Guide', link: '/guide' }],
#              });
#          - js-yaml FOR FRONT-MATTER — markdown files use
#            YAML front-matter for page metadata (title,
#            order, group, nav, hero, features, etc.); dumi
#            parses via js-yaml during build
#          - UMI 4 INTEGRATION — built on Umi (Ant Group's
#            production React framework); inherits Umi's
#            routing, plugin system, build pipeline, dev
#            server
#          - WEBPACK 5 + RSPACK/SWC SUPPORT — bundles via
#            Webpack 5 (default) or Rspack (faster) or swc
#            transpiler (faster than babel)
#          - 3 ROOT COMMANDS:
#              * dev          — start development server with
#                               HMR (hot module replacement)
#              * build        — build production-ready static
#                               site to dist/
#              * setup        — initialize new project /
#                               regenerate config files
#          - HMR (HOT MODULE REPLACEMENT) — markdown edits
#            reflect instantly without browser refresh; JSX
#            playground updates inline
#          - THEME-DEFAULT PACKAGE — default theme ships with
#            dumi; customizable via theme/* override files
#            (full Ant Design Pro doc theme)
#          - SHIKI SYNTAX HIGHLIGHTING — TypeScript-aware code
#            block highlighting via Shiki
#          - MARKDOWN-IT BASED — parses Markdown via markdown-
#            it (R667 headline lib) with custom remark/rehype
#            transformers for JSX live blocks + API tables
#          - INTERNATIONALIZATION — multi-language docs with
#            locale routing (e.g. /zh-CN/guide, /en-US/guide)
#          - CHINESE-ECOSYSTEM FLAGSHIP — dumi is the
#            documentation tool of choice for Ant Group's
#            open-source React component libraries (Ant
#            Design, Pro Components, ProForm, ProTable,
#            DvaJS, ahooks, formily, etc.).  Authoritative
#            within the Chinese React ecosystem.
#        Used by: Ant Design (THE production-grade Chinese
#        React library, 95k+ stars), Ant Design Pro, Ant
#        Design Mobile, ahooks (React hooks library), formily,
#        DvaJS, umi, ProForm, ProTable, and other Ant Group
#        / Umi.js ecosystem libraries.  Also as a reference
#        implementation of js-yaml + markdown-it + Umi 4 +
#        Webpack + React composition in TypeScript-Node.
#
# Author:  Umi.js team @ Ant Group — Chinese React framework
#          team.  dumi maintained by Jinbao1001 + xiaohuoni +
#          Yutengjing + ant-design-bot.  Current version
#          2.4.28; active development through 2026.
#          License: MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/umijs/dumi
#          https://github.com/umijs/dumi/blob/master/src/cli.ts
#          https://github.com/umijs/dumi/blob/master/src/service/cli.ts
#          https://github.com/umijs/dumi/blob/master/src/service/constants.ts
#          https://github.com/umijs/dumi/blob/master/package.json
#          https://d.umijs.org (official docs)
# CLI:     src/cli.ts + src/service/cli.ts — uses Umi's yParser
#          (yargs-parser fork) for argv parsing.  Headline
#          library: **js-yaml** (yargs-parser is documented
#          elsewhere; js-yaml is the new variant being
#          documented here, completing Axis 20 three-language
#          symmetry across Rust / Go / TS-Node).
# Library: js-yaml (https://github.com/nodeca/js-yaml —
#          "JavaScript YAML parser and dumper.  Very fast."
#           — Vitaly Puzrin (puzrin) + Alex Kocharin (rlidwka)
#           under the nodeca organization.  Distinct from
#           serde_yaml (R669, Rust Axis 20 opener) and
#           gopkg.in/yaml.v3 (R670, Go Axis 20 expansion) by
#           being:
#              1. CANONICAL NODE.JS YAML LIBRARY — js-yaml is
#                 the standard JavaScript YAML parser since
#                 2011 when Vitaly Puzrin ported the
#                 algorithm from PyYAML.  Distinct from:
#                 - yamljs (older, slower)
#                 - yaml (eemeli/yaml, modern alternative with
#                   AST access; lower adoption)
#                 - yaml-ast-parser (deprecated)
#                 js-yaml dominates by sheer installed-base
#                 inertia (Webpack, ESLint, Vue CLI, Gatsby,
#                 GitHub Actions runners, npm/yarn, etc. all
#                 use js-yaml).
#              2. PARSE + DUMP API — two top-level functions:
#                   import yaml from 'js-yaml';
#                   const parsed = yaml.load(text);
#                   const text = yaml.dump(parsed);
#                 Distinct from serde_yaml's serde-framework
#                 integration + yaml.v3's struct-tag mapping.
#                 js-yaml parses to plain JavaScript objects
#                 (POJOs); no schema-aware deserialization.
#              3. SCHEMA OPTIONS — yaml.load accepts a
#                 schema option: CORE (YAML 1.2 default), JSON
#                 (JSON-compatible types only), FAILSAFE
#                 (strings/arrays/maps only).  Distinct from
#                 yaml.v3's struct-tag-driven schema and
#                 serde_yaml's serde-driven schema.
#              4. CUSTOM TAGS via Type class — define custom
#                 YAML tags + their construction logic:
#                   import yaml from 'js-yaml';
#                   const colorType = new yaml.Type('!color', {
#                     kind: 'scalar',
#                     resolve: (data) => /^#[0-9a-f]+$/i.test(data),
#                     construct: (data) => ({ hex: data }),
#                     instanceOf: Object,
#                     represent: (color) => color.hex
#                   });
#                   const schema = yaml.DEFAULT_SCHEMA.extend([colorType]);
#                   yaml.load(text, { schema });
#                 Distinct from serde_yaml (no equivalent;
#                 serde framework handles custom types via
#                 #[derive] impls) and yaml.v3 (struct-tag
#                 customization via UnmarshalYAML interface).
#              5. SYNCHRONOUS PARSING — js-yaml is purely
#                 synchronous; no async/Promise API.  Suitable
#                 for build-time + CLI use; less suitable for
#                 streaming very large YAML files.  serde_yaml
#                 and yaml.v3 are also primarily sync.
#              6. LINE NUMBER + COLUMN ERROR REPORTING —
#                 yaml.YAMLException errors include line +
#                 column positions of parse failures.
#              7. SAFELOAD DEPRECATED — older versions exposed
#                 yaml.safeLoad / yaml.safeDump; modern (4+)
#                 js-yaml deprecated these because yaml.load /
#                 yaml.dump now use the safe CORE_SCHEMA by
#                 default.  Avoiding YAML deserialization
#                 attacks (a famous Ruby YAML vulnerability
#                 from 2013) requires this default.
#              8. BLOCK + FLOW STYLE SUPPORT — both:
#                   key1: value1     # block style
#                   key2: [a, b, c]  # flow style
#                 are parsed; dumping defaults to block style
#                 with options for flow.
#              9. ANCHOR + ALIAS SUPPORT — &anchor / *alias /
#                 << merge keys all parsed correctly;
#                 round-trip preservation when using yaml.dump
#                 with appropriate options.
#             10. VITALY-PUZRIN / NODECA ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE
#                 — Vitaly Puzrin (Russian developer) is THE
#                 maintainer of multiple foundational scientific
#                 JS libraries:
#                   * js-yaml          — YAML parser           (THIS)
#                   * markdown-it      — Markdown parser    (R667)
#                   * remarkable       — earlier markdown lib (deprecated)
#                   * pako             — zlib in pure JS
#                   * embedded-graphics — micro-display tooling
#                   * fontello          — icon-font generator
#                   * argparse-js       — argparse port to JS
#                 Vitaly Puzrin becomes a 2-LIBRARY AUTHOR in
#                 the taxonomy (after markdown-it R667).  His
#                 nodeca organization emphasizes "scientific" /
#                 data-engineering JavaScript libraries with
#                 careful spec compliance + minimal
#                 dependencies.  Distinct from Sindre Sorhus's
#                 1000+ small-package ecosystem, Titus Wormer's
#                 unified collective (remark / mdast), Daniel
#                 Stenberg's curl ecosystem, etc.)
# License: MIT (js-yaml); MIT (dumi)
# Status:  js-yaml — 6,584+ stars on nodeca/js-yaml, ~80M
#          weekly npm downloads (TOP-10 npm package by
#          downloads); foundational YAML library used by:
#            * Webpack (webpack.config.yaml + loader configs)
#            * ESLint (.eslintrc.yaml support)
#            * GitHub Actions (action.yml + workflow.yml in
